<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Marches to Quarterfinals after Beating Czech </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BRUSSELS, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Thierry Henry scored his second
goal of the championship to help world champion France beat the
Czech Republic 2-1 Friday, only one step up to the quarterfinals
in Euro 2000.
</P>
<P>
Henry, who scored in the team's opening 3-0 defeat of Denmark
last weekend, showed composure to give France the lead seven
minute into the game after a bad error by defender Petr Gabriel.
</P>
<P>
The Czechs equalised with a 35th minute penalty from Karel
Poborsky before the Arsenal forward crossed the ball from the left
for second-half substitute Youri Djorkaeff to score a crucial
second, 15 minutes into the second half.
</P>
<P>
With six points from two games in the Group D, the French is
now almost certain of a place in the last eight while the Czechs,
beaten finalists at Euro 96, have only a slim chance of avoiding
going home after the first round group stage.
</P>
<P>
France, who were beaten by the Czechs in the semifinals four
years ago after a penalty shootout, were stopped from playing the
same kind of fluent football which they displayed against the
Danes.
</P>
<P>
For a while at the start of the second half, the Czechs looked
capable of handing the French their first defeat for a year.
</P>
<P>
The first goal for France had some luck when Gabriel gave the
ball away to Henry 20 meters from goal and he took his chance,
sprinting into the right of the box and slotting the ball into the
far left-hand corner.
</P>
<P>
The Czechs tried to play most of their football from too deep
and, upset by the French pressing, they kept losing the ball
before they got within striking distance although Poborsky was
very busy in midfield and a constant danger.
</P>
<P>
In the 35th minute the Euro 96 finalists got some luck when
captain Didier Deschamps brought down Czech midfielder Pavel
Nedved. Before the penalty, the Czechs had had few real chances
apart from a Nedved shot in the second minute which French 'keeper
Fabien Barthez could only punch away.
</P>
<P>
After the goal they lifted their game. Poborsky went close
just before the break and at the start of the second half, Nedved
forced Barthez to make another good save.
</P>
<P>
But Djorkaeff's goal was a killer blow.
</P>
<P>
French defender Laurent Blanc should have added a third for
France 11 minutes from the end when he climbed unchallenged to a
right wing free kick from Djorkaeff only to direct his header wide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
