<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch Move to Last Eight by Beating Danes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The Netherlands cruised into the
quarterfinals on Friday in the European Championship after they
finally trounced Denmark 3-0 in group D.
</P>
<P>
Patrick Kluivert scored the first goal in the 58th minute at a
time when the Dutch showed signs of nerves. Substitute Ronald de
Boer added the second in the 66th soon after entering the game and
Boudewijn Zenden made it a hat-trick for Barcelona by adding the
third with 12 minutes left in 50,000 Feyenoord's De Kuip Stadium
in Rotterdam.
</P>
<P>
All the goals came as the Dutch upped the tempo after the
break following a first half when honours were largely even.
</P>
<P>
"It's good for our fans," Kluivert said. "We are a team and we
want to work for the coach. We proved that today.
</P>
<P>
"The intention was to win. We were satisfied with 1-0 but 3-0
is really fantastic. But after that we could possibly have scored
even more."
</P>
<P>
The first goal came from a break-away. Bergkamp had his shot
parried, but Kluivert was on hand to thump in the rebound.
</P>
<P>
With the Danes still in shock, the Dutch pounced nine minutes
later, a low Boudewijn Zenden cross from the left feeding Ronald
de Boer at the back post for the simplest of goals.
</P>
<P>
Zenden compounded Danish misery with a third goal for the
Dutch in the 77th minute after Michael Reiziger's impressive run
from the deep and a cross from the right.
</P>
<P>
Danish captain Michael Schonberg had the chance to pull one
back in the 80th minute after Dutch goalkeeper Edwin van der Sar
had brought down Ebbe Sand, but put his spot kick went just right
of the post.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch and France, who are also in the last eight after
beating the Czech Republic 2-1 earlier in the evening, will now
play for group D superiority in Amsterdam on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Both teams have six points, but since the French have scored
more goals, the Dutch will need a victory to win the group and
ensure they retain home advantage for the knock-out stage.
</P>
<P>
For the Danes, who suffered the same defeat in their opening
match against France, summer holidays begin next week, although
they first have the chance to win back some honour in the group's
wooden spoon contest with the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
The Danes looked marginally more threatening early on with
Jesper Gronkjaer on the left and Morten Bisgaard on the right
doing good work.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
