<HEADLINE> Lebanon Drums up Arab Support on Verification of Israeli Withdrawal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss
Saturday sought support from Arab countries in the United Nations
in handling verification of Israel's withdrawal from south Lebanon,
Lebanese National News Agency (LNNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Hoss called Arab League Secretary-General Esmat Abdel-Meguid
Saturday and briefed him of the result of the border inspection
carried out jointly by teams of Lebanese and U.N. experts.
</P>
<P>
During his telephone conversation with Meguid, Hoss said Israel
still occupies Lebanese territory at some parts of the border and
several pieces of Lebanese lands are still under Israeli control.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Meguid promised to urge Arab countries'
representatives in the United Nations to show support to Lebanon,
LNNA said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hoss said his country is determined to cooperate with
the U.N. but will not abandon any territory.
</P>
<P>
Hoss also met American and French ambassadors in Beirut and
asked them to deliver Lebanon's position on the border issue to
their countries.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said earlier Friday at U.N.
headquarters that the United Nations has confirmed the Israeli
withdrawal is complete.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council is scheduled to discuss a draft
statement endorsing Annan's confirmation of Israel's May 24
withdrawal from south Lebanon on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Also on Saturday, Hezbollah guerrillas said in a statement that
Annan's statement is not right and realistic but hasty and the
former anti-Israeli guerrilla group is "disappointed that the U.N.
covers Israel's continuous occupation of Lebanese land."
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah also stressed that it will "carry out all steps and
wait for a last result."
</P>
<P>
It warned that resistance is the best choice when "the
liberation is not completed and our land still under Israeli
control." 
</P>
