<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Due to the growing domestic and foreign demands, Iran
will produce 85 million square meters of tiles and ceramics in the
current Iranian calendar year (started on March 20), the Islamic
Republic News Agency reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Iran will be able to produce 115 million square meters of tiles
and ceramics per annum by the end of the third economic development
plan (March 2000-March 2005), said Mohammad Din Mohammadi,
managing-director of a tiles factory in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Mohammad said that his factory exported 2.5 million U.S. dollars
worth of tiles last year and it is expected to export the same
amount this year to Italy, Iraq, Afghanistan, Central Asian
republics and other countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Two Turkish construction companies, Akfen and Summa,
have completed renovation of the airport in Chisinau, capital of
Moldavia, reported Anatolia News Agency on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Moldavian President Petru Lucinschi inaugurated the
renovated airport, which will serve as a convenient gateway to the
country for foreign businessmen and tourists.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Akfen and Summa consortium, which won the tender for
the project, had the 12,000-square-metre terminal totally
renovated. New facilities include offices, VIP lounges, cafeterias-
restaurants- and high-tech-equipped customs checkpoints.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- The Algerian Airlines said it will start to operate
regular flights between Oran and Casablanca as of June 26 on the
basis of one flight every week.
</P>
<P>
The new route, which will fly Boeing-737 aircrafts, is expected
to continue operation until September 23, with a view to reducing
the costs of Algerian travellers to Morocco and to the Algerian
capital via Casablanca.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest statistics, 15,700 Algerians visited
Morocco last year, while 61,356 Moroccans visited Algeria.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- Saudi and Yemeni businessmen have launched projects to
establish joint ventures designed for marketing Saudi industrial
products, cultivating vegetables and fruits in Yemen, with a view
to covering the needs of the two countries for these products.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi company Alnemir is currently operating in Yemen's oil
sector, producing some 3,000 barrels of crude oil per day in oil
fields located in Shabwa province. The company is also conducting
surveys in other provinces.
</P>
<P>
The International Yemeni Company for Investments, which is
mostly owned by the Saudi Mahfouz Group, is another company
carrying out a major project in the Aden-based free trade zone. The
company spent 250 million U.S. dollars at least on the first phase
of the project.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Yemeni Ministry of Transport has chosen Saudi Bin
Laden group to implement a project of developing Aden international
airport, with a total cost estimated at 24 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The Saudi Industrial Development Bank (SIDB) has
approved to earmark about 697 million rials (182.8 million U.S.
dollars) as industrial loans to finance the creation of new
industrial projects and the expansion of existing ones.
</P>
<P>
The loans will cover seven industrial projects, including a
project for electricity distribution, the establishment of compact
power transfer plants, the electric power cutters for medium-sized
industries and the electric conductors in collaboration with the U.
S. General Electric company.
</P>
<P>
The bank is also planning to carry out a project for producing
welded steel pipes in cooperation with the Japanese Sumitomo
Industries company.
</P>
<P>
The projects also include two major schemes for the production
of petrochemicals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
