<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 17 (Xinhua) -- An Egyptian writer who has been
accused of insulting the Islamic holy book of Koran and the Prophet
Mohammed stood trial on Saturday before a state security court.
</P>
<P>
Salaheddin Mohsen, 43, is the author of four books describing
the Koran as the "holy book of Bedouin ignorance" and blaming Islam
for Arab countries' underdevelopment. He also called for the
creation of an Egyptian atheists' league.
</P>
<P>
Mohsen has been charged with offending divine religions and
threatening social peace, Egypt's official Middle East News Agency
said. If convicted, he may be sentenced to jail terms between six
months and five years and a fine of up to 300 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Mohsen was arrested in March at his home in the Sixth of October
town near Cairo after he published his book "The Shivering of the
Lights" through a private press at his own expense, the news agency
said.
</P>
<P>
Police also found several banned publications at his home.
</P>
<P>
Muslims believe the Koran, as revealed to Mohammed, is the
direct and unalterable word of God. 
</P>
