<HEADLINE> 138 Prisoners of War in Congo Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 17 (Xinhua) -- A total of 138 prisoners of war
held by belligerents in the war in the Democratic Republic of the
Congo (DRC) were released from Rwanda, the DRC and Zimbabwe,
Zimbabwean army spokesperson Chancellor Diye said Saturday in
Harare.
</P>
<P>
Diye was speaking to reporters on the release of 43 Rwandan
prisoners of war who had been held at the Field Airforce for the
past 19 months.
</P>
<P>
He said on June 16, 49 Rwandan prisoners of war were
repatriated from Kinshasa to Kigali, 35 Zimbabweans from Kigali
to Kinshasa, 11 Namibians from Kigali to Kinshasa and to
Windhoek.
</P>
<P>
The 43 ex-prisoners were seen off at the Harare International
Airport at about 3:00 p.m. by Red Cross and army officials of
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The release of the prisoners of war follows last week's
agreement between parties to the war in the DRC to exchange
prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
Diye said the arrival of the 35 Zimbabwean soldiers who were
being held as prisoners of war by Rwanda was delayed because of
technical hitches in Kinshasa. They are expected to reach here at
17:30 today, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean soldiers, together with those from Angola and
Namibia, have been in the DRC since August 1998 assisting the
government of Laurent Kabila to repel rebels being backed by
Rwanda and Uganda. 
</P>
