<HEADLINE> G-15 FMs Meet to Prepare for 10th Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The foreign ministers of the Group of
15 went into a meeting in Cairo on Saturday to prepare for the two-
day 10th summit of the organization, scheduled for early next week.
</P>
<P>
The ministers are set to deal with the agenda of the upcoming
summit and put the final touches on a joint communique to be issued
at the end of the gathering, Egypt's Middle East News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The G-15, founded in 1989, actually comprises of 17 developing
countries from Africa, Asia and Latin America, namely Algeria,
Egypt, Argentina, Brazil, Chile, India, Indonesia, Kenya, Jamaica,
Malaysia, Mexico, Nigeria, Peru, Senegal, Sri Lanka, Venezuela and
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The summit, due to open on Monday, will discuss world economic
development trends, globalization and G-15 members' policies,
elimination of poverty, reduction of debts, fight against
unemployment and inter-G-15 economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In an inaugural speech to the preparatory meeting, Egyptian
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa called on the G-15 member states to
step up cooperation in the economic, trade and investment fields
and coordinate stances on world economic and trade policies.
</P>
<P>
The G-15 members have a total population of 1.7 billion and
about 4,000 billion U.S. dollars of gross domestic product (GDP).
Their foreign trade stood at about 1,000 billion dollars in 1997
and the inter-member trade volume was estimated at 94 billion
dollars in 1998, accounting for less than 10 percent of the group's
total foreign trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
