<HEADLINE> Pakistan Allocates More Money to Agriculture Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Annual Development Plan of
Pakistan for the year 2000-2001 issued Saturday has allocated a
quarter more money for the agriculture sector than in the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
According to the Associated Press of Pakistan (APP), 329.15
million rupees (6.21 million U.S. dollars) has been allocated to
the Public Sector Development Program (PSDP) for agriculture,
showing a 24.6 percent leap from the figure for the period of July,
1999 to June, 2000.
</P>
<P>
Last year the PSDP allocation for agriculture sector was 289.12
million rupees (5.45 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, government policies for enhancing
agricultural productivity will be continued during 2000-2001.
</P>
<P>
Efforts will be made to increase the production particularly of
edible oilseeds in order to reduce its imports.
</P>
<P>
Support prices of agricultural commodities will continue to be
fixed in order to provide incentives to the farmers.
</P>
<P>
A growth rate of 3.9 percent has been projected for the
agriculture sector for the year in view the effect of water
shortage on the production of crops.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate of major and minor crops are projected at 3.2
percent and 6.9 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Livestock, fisheries and forestry are expected to grow by 2.8
percent, 7 percent and 3.1 percent respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
