<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Federal investigators on Friday found what they believe the
two computer hard drives containing nuclear secrets that have been
missing for more than a month from a vault at the Los Alamos
National Laboratory in New Mexico, U.S. government officials said.
</P>
<P>
-- Russian President Vladimir Putin proposed Friday that Europe
join the United States and Russia in creating an early warning
center in Moscow that would monitor missile launches around the
world.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The United Nations has certified Israel's withdrawal from
southern Lebanon, opening the way to a more robust U.N.
peacekeeping presence along Lebanon's often-troubled border with
Israel. But the certification was quickly challenged when
Lebanon's prime minister, Salim Hoss, contended in Beirut that
Israeli troops still controlled some parts of the border area.
</P>
<P>
-- The U.S. Senate voted unanimously Friday to approve a bill
that catapults electronic commerce to a new level by allowing
consumers and businesses to sign contracts online and know that
their e-signature is just as binding as one in ink. 
</P>
</TEXT>
