<HEADLINE> Palestinians Frustrated by Lack of Progress in Talks: Arafat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat said
here on Saturday that the Palestinian people have been frustrated
by the lack of progress in their peace talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Arafat told Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak during a meeting
that Israel is not moving in the final-status talks and fails to
make serious proposals on solving the thorniest issues of which
nothing has changed, Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr said after the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Arafat accused Israel of not being serious and not moving in any
of the main issues in the negotiations, including the final border
of a future independent Palestinian state, the status of Jerusalem,
Jewish settlements and the fate of Palestinian refugees, Moussa
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived in Cairo late Friday from Geneva to brief Mubarak
on his talks with U.S. President Bill Clinton in Washington on
Thursday. He often visits Egypt to consult with Mubarak on the
negotiations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
During his talks with Clinton, Arafat called on the United
States to pressure Israel into budging the peace process. Clinton,
however, turned down the demand.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. Mideast envoy Dennis Ross reportedly would visit
Israel early next week, followed by U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright later June, to assess if conditions are ripe for
a meeting of Clinton, Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the proposed summit, Arafat said there are many
difficulties and obstacles in its convocation. He added that
preparations have to be made to create suitable climate for it.
</P>
<P>
The summit is intended to seek breakthroughs in the Palestinian-
Israeli negotiations for a final peace treaty by September 13. The
two sides have made little progress in the so-called final-status
talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000617.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Official Urges to Combat Desertification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Environment Program
Saturday called for continued efforts in reinforcing partnership
with various agencies, community organizations and even
individuals worldwide to fight the menace of desertification.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Convention to Combat Desertification is the first
international treaty to focus on combating poverty and
environmental degradation in the rural areas in Africa, said
Executive Director Klaus Toepfe of the U.N. Environment Program.
</P>
<P>
In his message marking "World Day to Combat Desertification and
Drought", Toepfe said land degradation has affected some 1,900
million hectares of land worldwide and an estimated 500 million
hectares in Africa.
</P>
<P>
"The loss of potential productivity due to soil erosion
worldwide is estimated to be equivalent to some 20 million tons of
grain per year," he said.
</P>
<P>
The official noted that there are close linkages between
desertification and poverty, saying no long-term strategy of
poverty eradication can succeed in the face of environmental
forces that promote persistent erosion of the physical resources
upon which poor people depend.
</P>
<P>
He said human and natural causes together lead to the worsening
of desertification, citing that this should be quite clear now in
Kenya given the present drought affecting the country.
</P>
<P>
Prevention and control of desertification requires much more
than money, he said, stressing that science and technology are
fundamental to improve the management of drylands.
</P>
<P>
According to Toepfe, the challenge before the global community
is to design mechanisms to increase people's participation in
working out dryland management schemes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
