<HEADLINE> Foreign Exchange Reserves Continue to Decline in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 17 (Xinhua) -- India's foreign exchange
reserves dwindled further by 214 million U.S. dollars to 36.855
billion dollars for the week ended on June 9, 2000, as compared
with the previous week.
</P>
<P>
This was the eighth week in a row that the foreign exchange
reserves had shown a declining trend.
</P>
<P>
The Reserve Bank of India said Saturday that a fall in the
foreign currency assets by 214 million dollars to 34.002 billion
dollars was mainly responsible for the decline in the total
foreign reserves for the week.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, special drawing rights and gold reserves of the
country remained unchanged at 2 million dollars and 2.851 billion
dollars respectively in the reporting week as compared with the
previous week. 
</P>
