<HEADLINE> 5 Filipino Children Hostages Released: TV Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Five school children taken hostage
by the extremist Abu Sayyaf group were released Saturday morning
to government officials in the southern Philippines, a report of
the ABS-CBN television said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the hostages are heading toward a
still unidentified destination aboard two military choppers.
</P>
<P>
The five children were among some 50 people seized by the Abu
Sayyaf from two elementary schools in Basilan Province in March.
</P>
<P>
Some of the captives were released earlier by the extremist
group in exchange for food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
After the failure of peaceful efforts to secure the release of
the remaining hostages, which included teachers and a Catholic
priest, the military launched an assault on the Abu Sayyaf's
jungle hideout in Mount Puno Mohadje in April.
</P>
<P>
The clashes left dozens of soldiers and Abu Sayyaf gunmen dead.
Six hostages were also killed by the Abu Sayyaf although
government troops succeeded in rescuing several hostages.
</P>
<P>
The TV report said there are still three hostages remaining in
the hands of the Abu Sayyaf.
</P>
<P>
Another group of the Abu Sayyaf is now holding 21 mostly
foreign hostages in Sulu Province in the southern Philippines.
</P>
