<HEADLINE> Philippine Hostage Takers Accept Government Hostage Negotiator </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government confirmed
Saturday that the extremist Abu Sayyaf which is holding 21
hostages has accepted Secretary Robert Aventajado as chief
government negotiator for the hostages' release.
</P>
<P>
The Presidential Palace said in a press release that it hopes
negotiations to resume smoothly with this development.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the Abu Sayyaf said in a handwritten statement
that it was ready to accept Aventajado anew as the chief
negotiator after receiving the assurance that he would be "the
last person to favor military action" in resolving the hostage
situation.
</P>
<P>
According to the press release, the statement was signed by Abu
Sayyaf leaders Mujib Susukan and Commander Robot. It was hand-
carried by the group's emissaries to Manila and was personally
handed over to Aventajado.
</P>
<P>
Aventajado, chairman of the presidential flagships projects
committee, has been designated by President Joseph Estrada to lead
a government panel negotiating for the release of the mostly
foreign hostages kidnapped from Malaysia and brought to Sulu on
April 23.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf announced last week that it was rejecting
Aventajado as chief negotiator, pointing out that he was quoted by
the media as saying he would support a commando-type operation to
secure the hostages' freedom.
</P>
<P>
Aventajado, however, clarified that his statements were taken
out of context as he stressed that he would be the last person to
favor military action for the hostages' release.
</P>
<P>
President Estrada said earlier that Aventajado will stay on as
chief negotiator and reiterated that the government's paramount
concern remains the safety and welfare of the hostages.
</P>
<P>
The government also announced a three- to four-day cooling-off
period to review the Abu Sayyaf's conditions for the hostages'
release, which include the creation of an independent Islamic
state in Mindanao. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
