<HEADLINE> Manila Maintains No-Ransom Policy in Hostage Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Saturday that there is no plan by Malaysia or any foreign
government to pay ransom for the safe release of 21 hostages kept
by Abu Sayyaf extremists in the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora dismissed as hearsay news
reports that Malaysia had offered to pay 2.7 million U.S.dollars
for nine of the hostages, who are Malaysian nationals.
</P>
<P>
"That's not true, and the danger is that we are now reacting to
speculations instead of what is really happening," Zamora said in
a radio interview.
</P>
<P>
According to Zamora, President Joseph Estrada received an
assurance from Malaysian Foreign Minister Datuk Serisyed Hamid
Alvar during their meeting at the Presidential Palace Thursday
that Malaysia would not pay ransom.
</P>
<P>
He said the Malaysian official also assured the president that
there are no separate negotiations going on for the hostages'
release,as reported earlier.
</P>
<P>
"We talked to the Malaysian foreign minister two days ago. He
denied any separate negotiations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Fresh from a cooling-off period, government negotiators hope to
resume negotiations with the Abu Sayyaf this weekend for the
release of the hostages, said Zamora.
</P>
<P>
The 21 hostages, including three Germans, two French, two Finns,
two South Africans, a Lebanese, nine Malaysians and two Filipinos,
were kidnapped from an island resort off Sabah, Malaysia, on April
23 and taken to the Philippine island of Jolo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
