<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean President Refutes Seizure Of Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
said his government has no intention to seize foreign owned mines
but only wants to pursue its police of indigenity, the daily
Herald reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing his party's supporters in Kadoma in central
Zimbabwe, Mugabe accused the international media of misquoting him
as saying that the government would seize foreign owned mines.
</P>
<P>
"I was misquoted by the international press. I did not say we
were going to take the gold mines. I never said so," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I said we shall pursue the policy of empowerment and
indigenization with vigour," he said, adding "that means we want
to see more of our people entering manufacturing, mining and
commerce."
</P>
<P>
There won't be any seizure of gold mines, he said, stressing
that "what we would pursue is the policy of empowerment and
getting our multi-national companies to open up to some of the
black entrepreneurs."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the government would pursue with vigour the
policy of indigenity to speed up the economic empowerment of
blacks.
</P>
<P>
Independent, a british newspaper, reported this week that
President Mugabe said in an interview that after the land issue
was settled, the government would shift its attention to mines.
</P>
<P>
The story was widely quoted by other foreign media and
international news agencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
