<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Meets EU Fish Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Uganda has met all the European
Community requirements for lifting their ban on fish exports
imposed on the East African country in early 1999, the New Vision
newspaper reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Fish, water and sediment samples had been sent to the Food and
Research Institute of the Netherlands for laboratory analysis and
the results were good so far, State Minister for Agriculture and
fisheries Fred Mukisa was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said talks were going on between the European Union (EU)
fish importing countries and the Uganda government to work out
modalities to lift the ban.
</P>
<P>
"The Ministry of Agriculture, Food and Fisheries has done its
best to address all the requirements needed by the EU," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, a new Fisheries Bill to address all
weaknesses and loopholes in the existing law was in the offing.
</P>
<P>
Fisheries sector is one of Uganda's major export earners. The
ban imposed by the EU on imports of fish from Uganda has resulted
in a loss of more than 30 million U.S. dollars for the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000617.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Children Conditions Improved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The livelihood of Tanzanian
children has been improved but more needed to be done in this
regard, said Tanzanian Vice President Omar Ali Juma on Friday
while celebrating the African Child Day.
</P>
<P>
In a speech delivered at a gathering here, Juma said that the
infant death rate in Tanzania has reduced from 115 out of every
1000 children in 1990 to 91 last year.
</P>
<P>
Following a nationwide vaccination campaign, the death rate of
600 children below five years old out of every 100,000 children
born alive in 1978 was reduced to 42 last year, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that the death rate of pregnant women was
still as high as 52.9 percent due to poverty and poor
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
According to Juma, children's enrollment for primary education
has been increased from 72 percent in 1993 to 82 percent last year
but the number of those who completed the education was still low.
</P>
<P>
He called on all the communities in the country to observe the
rights of the children and try to alleviate poverty which has
stripped them of basic social services.
</P>
<P>
The vice president hailed the United Nations Children Fund
(UNICEF), Plan International and other non-governmental
organizations for their efforts in improving the livelihood of
Tanzanian children over the past years.
</P>
<P>
At the same function, Mwantunu Malale, Permanent Secretary of
the Ministry of Community Development, Women Affairs and Children,
said that children are the "seed bank" of the country and they
should be taken good care of to become future leaders and good
citizens.
</P>
<P>
Malale urged parents and guardians to regard their children not
only as decorations of their families but also as human beings
whose rights ought to be met.
</P>
<P>
The African Child Day is celebrated on June 16 every year
across the continent to commemorate the death of 15,000 children
killed on the same day in 1976 in Soweto town , South Africa when
they were protesting against the then apartheid regime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
