<HEADLINE> Kenya to Import 600,000 Tons of Maize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Following the suspension of duty
of imported maize by the government, millers in Kenya will import
600,000 tons of the product from South Africa in the forthcoming
months, local media reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The arrival of the maize from South Africa will see a drop in
the prices of maize and its flour by up to 15 percent, said Tahir
Sheikh Said, a leading miller in the country, on Friday in the
Indian Ocean port city Mombasa.
</P>
<P>
He explained that starting from August the price of a
90-kilogram bag of maize might drop to as low as 1,000 shillings
(about 13 U.S. dollars) and a 2-kilogram packet of maize flour to
about 46 shillings (about 60 U.S. cents) .
</P>
<P>
According to Sheikh Said, the first consignment of the imported
maize is expected to arrive in Mombasa on August 1.
</P>
<P>
Due to prolonged drought, millions of Kenyans are under the
threat of famine. Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi announced on
June 14 to waiver duty on imported maize to encourage millers to
import more of the product and build up the depleted food reserve.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
