<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Health News in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Following are the highlights of
major news on health care and medical research in China over the
past week:
</P>
<P>
HIV/AIDS May Become National Disaster in China
</P>
<P>
One of China's top AIDS experts has warned that the spread of
HIV/AIDS in the country will create a national disaster if the
number of virus carriers continues to swell while intervention
measures remain weak.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, China's number of carriers of the human
immunodeficiency virus (HIV), which leads to acquired immune
deficiency syndrome (AIDS), has increased yearly by 30 percent,
indicating that the country is experiencing a "fast growth period,
" said Prof. Zeng Yi of the Chinese Academy of Preventive Medicine.
</P>
<P>
Sino-British HIV/AIDS Project Launched in Beijing
</P>
<P>
China and Britain will jointly implement an AIDS program in two
Chinese provinces with an aim to create a model of disease
prevention, treatment and care for people vulnerable to HIV/AIDS
and sexually transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics of confirmed HIV infections in China were
18,143 at the end of March this year. But experts projected that
HIV/AIDS has affected at least 500,000 Chinese so far.
</P>
<P>
China to Enhance Adverse Drug Reaction Monitoring
</P>
<P>
China plans to enhance the surveillance of adverse drug
reactions (ADR) by improving the monitoring system nationwide and
urging pharmaceutical enterprises, drug stores and hospitals to
report ADR cases.
</P>
<P>
2000 Edition of Chinese Pharmacopoeia Published
</P>
<P>
The 2000 edition of "Chinese Pharmacopoeia" was officially
published by the State Drug Administration on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The content of the pharmacopoeia has been greatly updated. It
covers 2,691 kinds of Chinese and Western medicines, 399 more than
the previous edition.
</P>
<P>
Ophthalmic Diagnostic Consultation Center Opened
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Ophthalmic Diagnostic Consultation Center was
established on Friday at the Beijing Tongren Hospital, famous in
China for curing eye diseases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
