<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Health News in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ministry Redefines Subsidized Medicines
</P>
<P>
A new list of medicines covered by government-subsidized
medical care has been released by the Ministry of Labor and Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
Patients who rely on government subsidized-medical care are
limited to using these approved medicines, unless they are willing
to pay for those not on the list.
</P>
<P>
Fetus Discovered in Belly of 2-year-old Boy
</P>
<P>
Doctors with the Provincial Tumor Hospital in northeast China's
Heilongjiang Province have discovered a fetus in the belly of a 2-
year-old boy when performing a surgery meant to remove a "tumor"
in his body.
</P>
<P>
The lifeless fetus was not fully-developed yet and about the
size of a human fist.
</P>
<P>
Cataract Sufferers Benefit from Sino-US Clinic
</P>
<P>
The Sino-U.S. Boai Ophthalmology Clinic in the northern port
city of Tianjin has helped 20,000 cataract sufferers regain
eyesight with crystalline lens transplant operation with equipment
and expertise from the U.S.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Doctors Succeed in Non-thoracotomy Cardiac Surgery
</P>
<P>
By drilling three keyhole-size holes on the patient's right
chest, Chinese doctors have successfully conducted non-thoracotomy
surgery to treat auricular septal defects, a common congenital
heart disease.
</P>
<P>
The doctors inserted a thoracoscope through the hole with a
less than one centimeter in diameter to guide a blockade device
into the cardiac atriums.
</P>
<P>
Leukemia Sufferer Saved by Marrow from Taiwan Donator
</P>
<P>
A leukemia sufferer who received marrow donated by a Taiwanese
a month ago now recovered according to full-scale indexes of
hemogram.
</P>
<P>
Yao Meng, 25, was diagnosed leukemia last August and need
marrow transplant operation. However, no match has been found in
the mainland's marrow storage.
</P>
