<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak met
Saturday with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat. They were expected
to discuss the latest developments of the Palestinian-Israeli peace
talks and Arafat's recent meeting with U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
After a tete-a-tete session of talks, Mubarak and Arafat were
joined by their senior aides, including Egyptian Foreign Minister
Amr Moussa and Arafat's deputy, Secretary General of the Palestine
Liberation Organization Mahmoud Abass.
</P>
<P>
Details of the talks were not immediately available. But it was
expected that Arafat would brief the Egyptian leader on his meeting
with Clinton last Thursday at the White House and the ongoing
negotiations with Israel in the Washington area for a final peace
agreement scheduled for September 13 on thorny issues including
border, Jerusalem, Jewish settlements and Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
During his talks with Clinton, Arafat called on the U.S. to
pressure Israel into budging the peace process. Clinton, however,
turned down the demand. Meanwhile, U.S. Mideast envoy Dennis Ross
reportedly would visit Israel early next week, followed by U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright later June, to assess if
conditions are right for a meeting of Clinton, Arafat and Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived here late Friday. He frequently visits Cairo to
consult on the peace process with Mubarak and seek advice from him.
Egypt, the first Arab country to sign a peace treaty with Israel,
plays a key role in mediating the Palestinian-Israeli negotiations.
</P>
