<HEADLINE> Manila Expects Fish Self-Sufficiency This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Saturday that it has finished various fishery projects all over
the country to boost fish production and help achieve fish self-
sufficiency this year.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Secretary Edgardo Angara said his department is
accelerating fishery projects nationwide such as fish ports, ice
plants, cold storage facilities and fish port processing centers
to ensure a steady and affordable fish supply.
</P>
<P>
"The fishery sector's performance this year will likely be a
record-breaking feat with volume likely to reach 3.1 million
metric tons, up by 8.3 percent from the 2.86 million tons recorded
in 1999,"he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Angara said the construction of these fishery projects
amounting to 350 million pesos (8.75 million U.S. dollars) would
increase fish production and reduce fish wastage.
</P>
<P>
With higher production, the country may become self-sufficient
in fish this year, enabling millions of low-income Filiinos to
avail themselves of this affordable source of protein in their
diet, he added.
</P>
<P>
"If production growth trends are maintained, we may even become
a surplus producer and fish exporter before President Joseph
Estrada's term ends in 2004," Angara said.
</P>
<P>
Angara made the projection after the completion of some 35
major fisheries projects, which will directly address the problem
of wastage estimated at 15 to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
The country's fishery production grew by 3.7 percent last year.
The rise was one of the biggest recorded for the sector in the
1990s considering the fact that the 1998 growth rate barely stood
at 0.71 percent and the country even suffered a production decline
of 0.09 percent in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
