<DOCNO> XIE20000617.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Why Indian Rupee Continues to Fall? by Xiong Changyi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Indian rupee, which lost 2.7
percent of its value during the 1999-2000 fiscal year, has
continued to fall and slid by nearly 2.5 percent since early May
due to a widening trade gap and shrinking foreign direct
investment.
</P>
<P>
The rupee exchange rates, which dropped from 43.68 rupees per U.
S. dollar on May 9 to 44.06 rupees the next day, further plunged
to a record low of 44.95 rupees per dollar on June 8, but
recovered to close at 44.7 per dollar Friday.
</P>
<P>
A study undertaken by the Association Chambers of Commerce and
Industry of India recently predicted that the rupee will come
under further pressure to stabilize at between 46.5 and 47 rupees
toward the end of this fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the most important sign of the pressure on the
rupee comes from the trade front. In the 1999-2000 fiscal year,
which ended on March 31, the country was able to hold down the
trade deficit at 8.6 billion dollars despite a 65-percent increase
in the oil bill.
</P>
<P>
But they said the stable level of trade deficit was mainly due
to the fact that the non-oil imports rose by only 1.7 percent
although exports went up by 11.7 percent in the previous fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
However, the latest figures indicate that this advantage is
unlikely to persist in the current fiscal year. The trade deficit
in April, the first month of fiscal 2000-2001, doubled to 1.1
billion dollars as against 500 million dollars in the same period
last year. This was because the import bill surged to 43.6 percent
though exports went up by 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the non-oil imports were also gaining momentum for
the first time in two years and suddenly recovered by 25.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
As against an estimated 11 billion dollars, the actual bill of
oil imports is expected to range between 13 billion and 16 billion
dollars in the current fiscal.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the consequence of both these factors would be a
sharp increase in trade deficit in this fiscal year and further
downward pressure on the rupee.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with BBC, Indian Finance Minister Yashwant
Sinha said, "I am not worried as such about what is happening in
the foreign exchange market on a temporary basis. What worries me
is the long-term trend."
</P>
<P>
However, he said he expected the current pressure on the rupee
to ease. "There must be an inflow of fresh funds and from whatever
information I have, I have reasons to hope that the flow of funds
will improve and therefore the pressure that we are seeing on the
rupee should go away," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000617.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
