<DOCNO> XIE20000617.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Record-Breaking Heatwave Takes Toll of Nine in California </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Barbara Pletz, director of Emergency Medical Services for San
Mateo County just south of San Francisco, said the victims were
all elderly and that they were apparently succumbed to
complications from the record-breaking heat that scorched the area
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Two people died at a local nursing home which did not have air
conditioning, while others died after attempting yard work in
temperatures that went as high as 109 degrees Fahrenheit.
</P>
<P>
"I've never seen anything like this and I've been in this job
12 years," Pletz said Friday. "It is very clear to us that we had
a very, very severe problem."
</P>
<P>
San Francisco, which likes to boast that it has "natural air
conditioning" thanks to its usually cool and foggy coastal climate,
sweltered through an unusual heatwave Wednesday as temperatures
smashed records across northern California.
</P>
<P>
In downtown San Francisco, the temperature broke an all-time
record for the date of 103 degrees Fahrenheit -- tying the record
for the hottest day ever since the city began keeping records in
1871.
</P>
<P>
Officials and emergency medical technicians around the area
said the record-breaking heat was definitely a factor in a region
which usually enjoys famously cool summers. Many expected the
final toll to rise as more deaths are reported.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologists said the heatwave, which began on Tuesday and
spiked on Wednesday, was due to a high pressure ridge that stalled
over the region, shutting down sea breezes which normally blow
cooling fog over the San Francisco area.
</P>
<P>
That fog began rolling back Thursday, pushing coastal
temperatures down some 40 degrees to relatively normal levels in
the mid-60s.
</P>
<P>
The National Weather Service said temperatures in the area were
expected to remain normal throughout the weekend, although next
week could see the heat turned up again.  
</P>
</TEXT>
