<HEADLINE> Poland Appoints New Defense Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Polish President Aleksander
Kwasniewski, upon a suggestion by Prime Minister Jerzy Buzek
during a cabinet shakeup, appointed Ronislaw Komorowski as the new
defense minister Friday to replace Janusz Onyszkiewicz.
</P>
<P>
President Kwasniewski thanked former Defense Minister
Onyszkiewicz for his efforts to work for Poland's entry into NATO,
but he criticized sharply the recent work of the Defense Ministry,
media reports said.
</P>
<P>
Kwasniewski said the top priority for the new defense minister
is to strengthen the position of Poland in NATO, to modernize the
army by finding more capital and to carry on internal reforms.
</P>
<P>
The reports said President Kwasniewski on the same day also
appointed Jerzy Kropiwnicki as the minister of regional
development and housing, who retains the post as the head of the
Center for Strategic Studies.
</P>
<P>
The government reshuffle came after the Freedom Union (UW),
Poland's second largest party, broke away from the ruling
coalition, the Solidarity Election Action (AWS), the largest party
led by Prime Minister Jerzy Buzek, over rows of economic reforms.
The collapse of the coalition led to the collective resignation of
five UW cabinet ministers on May 28.
</P>
<P>
The five ministers included Deputy Prime Minister and Finance
Minister Leszek Balcerowicz, Foreign Minister Bronislaw Geremek,
and Defense Minister Janusz Onyszkiewicz.
</P>
<P>
Their resignation had been criticized as irresponsible before
it was finally accepted by President Kwasniewski on June 6, when
he appointed Economy Minister Janusz Steinhoff as deputy prime
minister and three other AWS officials as new ministers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
