<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pacers Stay Alive With Win In NBA Finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 16 (Xinhua) -- For the sixth time in nine
playoff elimination games this season, the Los Angeles Lakers came
up short, losing to the Indiana Pacers 120-87 Friday night in Game
5 of the NBA Finals, trimming their lead to 3-2.
</P>
<P>
The Lakers, who lost two games to the Sacramento Kings, another
to the Phoenix Suns and two more to the Portland Trail Blazers
once they got within one game of winning those series, seemed a
step slow on this night, especially on defense.
</P>
<P>
Before Game 5, Lakers coach Phil Jackson admitted that with a 3-
1 lead, it was difficult to keep his team from being overconfident,
especially considering the Lakers haven't lost three straight
games since the 1999 playoffs.
</P>
<P>
Following developments confirmed exactly what he predicted.
</P>
<P>
Friday night, the Lakers, as a team, obviously didn't play with
all their strength and let the Pacers stay alive for the time
being, partly because this way they can clinch the NBA
championship during one of the final two games at home, according
to a source close to the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
The Lakers fan in Los Angeles, with the Monday ticket for Game
6, are so nutty over dramatic endings at Staples Center in Los
Angeles. Preparation for a grand celebration is underway.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, it was sure that, led by Jalen Rose, the
Pacers put on a fantastic shooting display that helped to keep the
Lakers' championship plans on hold.
</P>
<P>
Starting 6-for-6 on 3-pointers and shooting 75 percent in the
first quarter, the Pacers manhandled the Lakers by as much as 33
points Friday night.
</P>
<P>
"We didn't want to see the Lakers celebrate on our court," said
Rose, "We're a team that plays better when our backs are against
the wall, and 3-1 was a big wall."
</P>
<P>
"We have absolutely nothing to lose and everything to gain,"
said his teammate Raggie Miller. "Everybody expects us to lose
anyway, let's let it hang out and have fun."
</P>
<P>
Shaquille O'Neal scored 35 for the Lakers but Kobe Bryant,
overtime hero of Game 4 despite a sprained ankle, got only eight
points Friday night.
</P>
<P>
Miller refused to take credit for Bryant's poor showing. "I
think Kobe Bryant held himself to eight points. He had a lot of
good looks," said Miller.
</P>
<P>
Game 6 will be Monday night at Los Angeles and Game 7, if
necessary, will be Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
No team has ever come back from a 3-1 deficit in the finals,
but the Pacers look to be a strong candidate to be the first if
they can shoot as well as they did Friday night.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
