<HEADLINE> Canada, U.S. Reach New Defense, Satellite Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Canada and the United States
reached new agreements on defense and satellite operations Friday
in Washington, according to the Canadian government.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy and U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright exchanged notes on the extension of the
North American Aerospace Defense (NORAD) Agreement for another
five years from its current expiry date of May 12, 2001, said the
government announcement.
</P>
<P>
In his own statement, Axworthy said "NORAD has been the
foundation of Canada-U.S. defense cooperation since 1958" and the
extension" reflects the special relationship we enjoy with the
United States and is a natural complement to the extensive
political, economic and social ties that link our two countries."
</P>
<P>
Axworthy and Albright also signed an agreement on the operation
of commercial remote sensing satellite systems.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement released here Friday, the two countries
said that the agreement is aimed at fostering "broad private uses
of commercial remote sensing satellite systems, while protecting
common national security and foreign policy interests."
</P>
<P>
"The agreement essentially applies to high-performance earth
observation satellites used for such purposes as cartography, land-
use and, natural resource and environment management. It does not
apply to meteorological, navigation or communications satellites,"
said the joint statement.
</P>
<P>
One of the key operations under the agreement is that of
RADARSAT-2, a Canadian synthetic aperture radar satellite system
to be launched by a U.S. commercial space launch vehicle in 2003,
according to the Canadian government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
