<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Major Legal Events in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) government
has legal powers to tackle most forms of reported computer crimes
and will continue to tackle the problem vigorously, said Regina Ip,
secretary for security of Hong Kong, Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the "The Asian Securitex 2000 Conference," Ip said
unauthorized access to a computer by telecommunication, or what is
commonly known as hacking, is a criminal offense under the
Telecommunication Ordinance that carries a maximum fine of 20,000
HK dollars (2,560 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
HK Legislature Passes Amended Arbitration Bill
</P>
<P>
The Arbitration (Amendment) Bill 2000 was passed in the
Legislative Council of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR) Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The bill seeks to make it possible that with the leave of the
court, arbitral awards made either in or outside Hong Kong are
summarily enforceable in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
China to Formulate Law on Popularization of Sciences
</P>
<P>
China's top legislative body has a law in the works on the
dissemination of sciences among the general public, totaling 1.3
billion people, senior officials said in Beijing Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Yutai, vice-chairman of the China Association for
Science and Technology, said he was among a group of lawmakers,
legal experts and scientists on a recent tour of Nanjing, the
capital of east China's Jiangsu Province, and Shanghai to gain
information which would help them to draft the law.
</P>
<P>
China to Hold National Exams for Wardens
</P>
<P>
China's Ministry of Justice will hold its first national
examinations for prison police in November this year, and those
who failed in the exams will be removed from the posts, a ministry
official said in Beijing Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The exams, focusing political theories, legal knowledge,
professional skills, are aimed at enhancing the proficiency level
of the country's prison wardens, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
