<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Putin Ends His Visit to Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BERLIN, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The Russian President Vadimir
Putin ended his visit to Germany on Friday and left for Moldava.
</P>
<P>
During his three-day visit Putin had talks with German
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, President Johannes Rau, the former
Chancellor Helmut Kohl and leaders of German business.
</P>
<P>
The visit opened a new chapter in the bilateral relations.
Russia and Germany are both big European countries and the
bilateral relations play a very important role in their foreign
policies.
</P>
<P>
"We want a comprehensive new start to German-Russian relations,
" said Schroeder at a joint news briefing after his talks with
Putin.
</P>
<P>
And Putin said : "Germany remains our leading partner in
Europe and the world."
</P>
<P>
Although Putin had stressed before his visit that he would not
develop private friendship, he invited Schroeder to make a private
visit to Moscow with family over Christmas. Schroeder accepted
Putin's invitation and two families will gather in Moscow at
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
About the question of the proposed U.S. National Defense
Missile system Schroeder said he and Putin had agreed firmly the
current arms control accord needed to be observed and to prevent a
new arms race.
</P>
<P>
The proposed National Defense Missile system of the United
States will install radar sites and 100 interceptors based in
Alaska which could shoot down missiles fired at the U.S. by so-
called rogue states. Both Russia and Germany are opposed to the
plan and they expressed this would harm the 1972 signed Anti-
Ballistic Missile (ABM) Treaty by the former Soviet Union and the
United States. The treaty strictly limited such systems. Putin and
Schroeder fear it could set off a new arms race.
</P>
<P>
Russia called for a system of more limited Theater Missile
Defense (TMD) system which would guard only against shorter-range
missiles.
</P>
<P>
Putin warned Europe in his speech to be opposed to the U.S.
NMD and reaffirmed Russia's opposition to any further NATO
enlargement. Because three states of the former Warsaw Pacts, the
Czech Republic, Hungary and Poland had been received as the new
members of the NATO last spring and the NATO will still enlarge
eastwards and is prepared to receive more Eastern and Southeastern
European states into the organization in the future years. Russia
is firmly against the eastwards enlargement of the NATO.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder has also expressed his big concern over the U.S. NMD
proposal. He had stated his attitude to Bill Clinton while Clinton
visited Berlin earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
About Putin's proposal Schroeder said : "We found the
recommendation made by President Putin are really worthy of
consideration." But Schroeder stressed that it should not harm the
friendly relations between Germany and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The economic and trade relations are another main issue of the
bilateral talks. The Russian natural gas giant Gazprom had signed
a memorandums of understanding with several German companies at in
the presence of Putin and Schroeder earlier.
</P>
<P>
Germany is the biggest creditor of Russia. Russia owes German
banks 75 billion marks (37 billion dollars). According to German
officials there was no agreement on rescheduling of Russian debt
and the resumption of German state "Hermes" export guarantees.
But it was said earlier that it could come to an agreement on the
Russian debt.
</P>
<P>
About the return of the German cultural and art treasures
there was no progress. "We are prepared to continue this dialogue,
" said Putin and added :"We must move toward each other."
</P>
<P>
Russia and Germany agreed to set up a commission to discuss
this question further this autumn.
</P>
<P>
Putin and Schroeder has agreed they will meet again next April
in St. Petersburg. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000617.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Needs Reforms to Welcome Newcomers: French FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Visiting French Foreign Minister
Hubert Vedrine said here on Friday that the European Union (EU)
needs reforms to clear the way for its eastern expansion.
</P>
<P>
In a speech at the Czech Foreign Ministry, Vedrine said that
before substantial talks on the EU's eastern expansion, the EU
must complete its internal reforms first.
</P>
<P>
While setting the deadline for EU reforms by the end of this
year, Vedrine refused to give a timetable for the EU to accept new
members.
</P>
<P>
"It is not appropriate to set such a timetable for the EU,"
Vedrine stressed. He also indicated at a meeting with Czech Prime
Minister Milos Zeman that the EU will not be able to accept new
members until January 1, 2003.
</P>
<P>
The French foreign minister arrived in Prague Thursday for a 3-
day visit before his upcoming inauguration on July 1 as the new EU
chairman.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine's visit came when applicants for EU membership are
growing more and more impatient with the EU's eastward expansion.
Such applicant countries as the Czech Republic insist that the EU
stick to its promise to accept new members at the beginning of
2003 and complete accession negotiations with those applied first
by the end of 2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
