<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique House Projects for Flood Victims Awaits Promised Funding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Houses will be built within six
months in Kongolote, a suburb of the southern Mozambican city of
Matola, for more than 5,000 victims of February's floods, when
promised funding from Western donors is made available, said
Silvano Langa, director of the National Disasters Management
Institute (INGC).
</P>
<P>
He said that it would be ideal to have houses built by October
before the next rainy season starts.
</P>
<P>
Almost all victims to be resettled used to live in flimsy
houses in the outer suburbs of Matola which were flooded out in
the February deluge.
</P>
<P>
Speaking during the visit of U.S. Treasury secretary Lawrence
Summers, who arrived in Maputo on Friday, Langa said that if the
next rainy season starts before the houses are built, these people
will be rendered homeless again because the tents, which house
three to four families each, will be damaged by that time.
</P>
<P>
Langa said that the situation in Kongolote is similar to that
of other accommodation centers in the flooded areas in the
southern and central regions of the country.
</P>
<P>
However, Langa expressed optimism about a swift disbursing of
the funds pledged by donors at the Rome conference in May, saying
that Summers' visit "is as good sign."
</P>
<P>
The United States is the biggest donor, pledging to provide 131
million out of the promised 452.9 million U.S. dollars for
resettlement and infrastructures reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
Talking to the displaced in Kongolote, Summers said that he was
well aware of the full drama they had experienced, through the
images of the floods he had seen on television.
</P>
<P>
During his two-day visit to Maputo, Summers is also to meet
with President Joaquim Chissano. 
</P>
</TEXT>
