<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poland to Hold Presidential Elections on October 8 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Poland will start presidential
elections on October 8 this year, Macie Plazynski, speaker of the
House of Representatives announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
As to the agenda of elections, Plazynski said that election
commissions must be registered before August 14 and candidates
must be registered with the national election commission before
the midnight of June 24.
</P>
<P>
The Constitution of Poland gives each president a five-year
term and the incumbent Aleksander Kwasniewski, who came to power
on November 19, 1995, will soon finish his mandate.
</P>
<P>
The Polish people choose their president through general and
direct suffrage. Polish citizens above 18 are eligible for vote
and a citizen above 35 can become a presidential candidate if he
successfully musters no less than 100,000 signatures of supporters.
A party candidate should be backed by a 15-member election
commission.
</P>
<P>
Up till now, a dozen of politicians have announced to run for
the office, including Kwasniewski, former President Lech Walesa,
former foreign minister and economist Andrzej Olechowski, former
premier Jan Olszewski and Solidarity Election Action Union leader
Marian Krzaklewski and Chairman of Peasant Party Jaroslaw
Kalinowski.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest poll, the left wing-supported President
Kwasniewski will win in the first round with 69 percent of the
votes and Walesa will get only two percent.
</P>
<P>
Were parliament to be elected now, the ruling National
Committee of Solidarity Election Action Union would get but 13
percent of the votes while the opposition left wing union would
get 45 percent, the poll said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
