<DOCNO> XIE20000617.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Orders All Foreign Troops Leave DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Friday unanimously adopted a resolution which demands all foreign
troops, especially the Rwandan and Ugandan forces, withdraw from
the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
The resolution was adopted at the end of the two-day talks
between Security Council members and all the conflicting parties,
with the presence of foreign ministers or senior government
officials from six African countries involved in the 22-month-long
DRC fighting.
</P>
<P>
The resolution demanded that Rwanda and Uganda pull out all
their troops "without further delay," but it said that each phase
of the withdrawal of Rwandan and Ugandan forces should be
reciprocated by other armies in the central African country,
according to the timetable set forth in the Lusaka Cease-fire
Agreement, signed in July last year.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda and Uganda backed rebels in fighting against the DRC
Government of President Laurent Kabila, who were supported by
Angola, Namibia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The resolution also said that Rwanda and Uganda should make
reparations for the "loss of life and property damage they had
inflicted on civilians" in Kisangani of northeastern DRC, which is
known as the nation's diamond trade center.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation Security Council expressed "its readiness to
consider possible measures which could be imposed" to enforce
compliance with its demand, said the resolution. However, it did
not specify what the possible measures are despite the statement
the Council was acting under Chapter Seven of the U.N. Charter.
</P>
<P>
The Chapter Seven of the U.N. Charter stipulates punitive and
mandatory measures, including economic and diplomatic sanctions
and other military options if sanctions are not enough.
</P>
<P>
The resolution also called on the DRC Government to allow full
participation of all political factions in a national dialogue as
called for in the Lusaka Agreement.
</P>
<P>
The DRC Government should cooperate with former Botswana
President Ketumile Masire, the facilitator for the talks who were
appointed by the Organization of African Unity (OAU). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
