<HEADLINE> Chinese Science News: Weekly Highlights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Following are the highlights of
major science stories released by Xinhua this week:
</P>
<P>
CAS, Prestigious Universities to Build High-Tech Center
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) will cooperate with
Beijing and Qinghua universities to promote the development of
high-tech industries.
</P>
<P>
CAS, Beijing and Qinghua universities, a high technology
development office attached to the Ministry of Science and
Technology and the Haidian District People's Government signed an
agreement today to build a high-tech development center and
websites to facilitate information.
</P>
<P>
CAS and the two universities will provide five high-tech
projects to the high-tech development center, while the Ministry
of Science and Technology and the Haidian District People's
Government will provide funds and the area for the center.
</P>
<P>
Humankind Under Threat of Geochemical Hazards: Scientist
</P>
<P>
A Chinese scientist has warned that human beings may be
threatened by outbreaks of geochemical hazards if they fail to
control the amount of harmful materials released into the soil.
</P>
<P>
Geochemical hazards have been called "chemical time bombs" by
some European scientists because they may suddenly burst forth due
to the long-term accumulation of harmful materials in the earth,
causing massive damage to agricultural production and people's
health.
</P>
<P>
Science Publishing Prepares For WTO Entry
</P>
<P>
Writers and publishers of science books and magazines for
general audience are trying to prepare their industry for China's
entry into the World Trade Organization(WTO).
</P>
<P>
Due to lack of creativeness and vividness, China's science
publications usually attract few readers.
</P>
<P>
After China joins WTO, some protective policies enjoyed by
Chinese publishers, such as limits of market entry on foreign
publications and protective prices will no longer exist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000617.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Science News: Weekly Highlights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Scientists Complete Genetic Linkage Map of Common Carp
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists said recently that they have already drawn a
genetic linkage map of common carp, making it possible for
fostering new species of carp with some good characters.
</P>
<P>
Researchers with Heilongjiang Branch of Chinese Academy of
Fishery Sciences crossbred two species of carps and got the
individual of hybrid, from which they pick up haploid DNA and then
got the genetic linkage map after computer analysis on the DNA.
</P>
<P>
Arsenic Might Cure Liver Cancer: Expert
</P>
<P>
Chinese expert recently found that the virulent arsenic might
be a good medicine for liver cancer if used properly.
</P>
<P>
Liu Lianxin, doctor with Harbin Medical Sciences University (
HMSU) in northmost Heilongjiang province, announced to have found
that arsenic will kill cells of liver cancer.
</P>
<P>
In his experiments, Liu observed liver cancer cells in arsenic
environment of different density and found that arsenic with light
density will induce the death of cells. He further found that the
arsenic in fact cause changes on a kind of enzyme, which mainly
account for the death of cancer cells.
</P>
<P>
Scientists Locate Origin of Sediments in Yellow River
</P>
<P>
Chinese water control experts have found that grit in the
middle reaches of the Yellow River is mainly to blame for the
accumulation of sediments in this China's second longest river.
</P>
<P>
Based on four years' field study and intensive analysis of data
collected, the water control experts concluded that most of the
sediments in the Yellow River come from the 78,600-sq-km gritty
area in the middle reaches of the river. The discovery would pave
the way for effective sediments-control in the future, they said.
</P>
<P>
Science, Education Top Priority for China's Western Development:
Li
</P>
<P>
Chinese vice premier Li Lanqing has stressed the importance of
science, technology and education reforms in developing western
China this week.
</P>
<P>
Li, also a member of the standing committee of the Chinese
Communist Party central committee, made these remarks during his
four-day inspection tour of Chongqing, the largest industrial city
in west China.
</P>
<P>
Li said further educational reforms are needed to produce all
kinds of professionals for the ongoing massive development in
China's west.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
