<DOCNO> XIE20000617.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Environment News: Weekly Highlights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China will start a five-year sand-control project on the
outskirts of the capital to improve the environment, the State
Forestry Administration announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
The project involves 116 counties in Beijing, Tianjin, Hebei
Province,the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region and Shaanxi Province,
covering an area of some 464,000 square km.
</P>
<P>
When the project is completed, the coverage rate of trees and
grass will increase from 13.36 percent to 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
HK Gov't Funds Air Quality Improvement Strategy
</P>
<P>
The Finance Committee of Legislative Council of Hong Kong
Friday approved a new commitment of 725.52 million HK dollars (
about 93.02 million U.S. dollars) for providing a one-off grant to
encourage diesel taxi owners to replace their vehicles with
liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) vehicles.
</P>
<P>
A government spokesman said that the grant to assist taxi
owners to replace their diesel taxis with LPG taxis forms part of
the overall strategy to improve air quality.
</P>
<P>
A one-off grant of 40,000 HK dollars (about 5,128 U.S. dollars)
would be provided to each diesel taxi that was replaced by a LPG
one, the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
New Plan Unveiled to Tackle Deserts
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has unveiled a new environmental plan
to reduce desert areas and prevent dust storms in north China,
dividing the target areas into four different ecosystems and come
up with four corresponding strategies to address the problems.
</P>
<P>
The four ecosystems are the capital circle, the agriculture and
animal husbandry belt, the grassland belt and the desert and oasis
belt.
</P>
<P>
According to the strategies, the capital circle, which includes
the two municipalities of Beijing and Tianjin and the two cities
of Zhangjiakou and Chengde in Hebei province, will be planted with
more trees, grass and flowers over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
Fall Webworms Threaten Trees in North China
</P>
<P>
Fall webworms, a United States indigenous pest and listed as
one of the world's six most dangerous pests., are on a rampage in
north China's port city of Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
The hot, dry weather has created prime conditions for the
reproduction of the plant-eating white moth with black-spotted
wings.
</P>
<P>
"If we lose the first battle against the first generation of
fall webworms by the end of this month, we will lose everything,"
said Chen Jingang, an official with the municipal gardening
administration.
</P>
<P>
Beijing Strengthens Environment Protection
</P>
<P>
Investment in environmental protection in this Chinese capital
is expected to exceed 100 billion yuan (12 billion U.S. dollars)
between 1998 and 2007, accounting for more than four percent of
the city's Gross Domestic Product (GDP) for the ten-year period.
</P>
<P>
For the first five years during the ten-year period, Beijing
will inject 46.6 billion yuan into the environmental protection
endeavor, to reduce pollution in air and water, and facilitate
garbage disposal and industrial restructuring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
