<HEADLINE> Chinese Environment News: Weekly Highlights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The nature reserve will protect the ecology, wild animals and
plants, and ensure sufficient water supply in the middle and lower
reaches of the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
"We should have an overall plan for the nature reserve," said
Liu Jiyuan, director of the Institute of Geographical Sciences and
Natural Resources of the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
 Liaoning Bans Non-degradable Products
</P>
<P>
Starting July 1, northeast China' s Liaoning Province will ban
plastic tableware to cut back on the pollution produced by such
non-degradable products.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, bio-degradable materials such as paper, plant fiber,
and starch are officially recommended to replace plastics for
making tableware and degradable plastic bags.
</P>
<P>
About one billion sets of plastic tableware and more than 100,
000 tons of plastic bags are sold in Liaoning annually, accounting
for one tenth of the nation's total. These plastic items seriously
threaten the local environment, since it will take about 200 years
for them to degrade.
</P>
<P>
Landslide in Tibet Triggers Lake Dam Breach
</P>
<P>
The dam of the Yigung Lake in the Nyingchi Prefecture of Tibet
Autonomous Region breached on June 11, seriously damaging roads
and bridges in areas at the lower reaches of the lake.
</P>
<P>
No casualty has been reported due to precautionary evacuation
of local residents, local sources said.
</P>
<P>
The breach was caused by surging water level as a result of
piled-up mud and stones in the lake from the landslide of a nearby
mountain in April.
</P>
<P>
First Tip for Hazardous Industrial Garbage in China
</P>
<P>
The first tip for dangerous industrial garbage in China has
been built in this capital city of northeastern China's Liaoning
Province.
</P>
<P>
With an area of 130,000 sq. meters, the tip is designed to
handle 20,000 tons of nocuous solid garbage annually and can
accept such dangerous items as metals, acid or alkaline garbage
for up to 12 years with a total handling capacity of 240,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Built with 6.44 million US dollars in world bank loans and 84
million yuan of Chinese counterpart fund, the tip was meant to be
a demonstration project for similar projects in other Chinese
cities.
</P>
<P>
Northeast China Steps up Pollution Reduction in Rivers
</P>
<P>
 The heavy pollution in the Songhua and Liao rivers in
northeast China is expected to be greatly eased in the next five
years as more than a half of the cities in the Songhua-Liao river
valley build their own sewage treatment plants.
</P>
<P>
So far, Shenyang, capital of Liaoning, has built such a plant
in its northern area, which handles 400,000 tons of sewage daily.
Changchun, capital of Jilin, is also building a sewage treatment
plant with a daily handling capacity of 390,000 tons.
</P>
</TEXT>
