<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Environment News: Weekly Highlights (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The combined area of the two new nature reserves of the Naban
River and the Wuliang Mountain, and the nature reserves of Baima
Snow Mountain and Gaoligong Mountain to be expanded will add 432,
500 hectares to the province's State-level nature reserves.
</P>
<P>
The 26,000-hectare Naban River Nature Reserve located in the
famous Dai Autonomous Prefecture of Xishuangbanna, boasts more
than 1,700 high plants and 227 vertebrates. The Wuliang Mountain
Nature Reserve has some 400 black-crowned gibbons which are under
State protection.
</P>
<P>
Largest Sewage Treatment Plant in SW China Begins Operation
</P>
<P>
The largest sewage disposal plant in western China was put
into use recently in Chengdu, the capital of southwestern Sichuan
Province.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the plant, which is capable of handling 300,000
cubic meters of waste water a day, or 40 percent of the city's
total, began three years ago.
</P>
<P>
Located in the southern suburbs of Chengdu, the plant covers an
area of 28.9 hectares. It cost 465 million yuan (about 56 million
U.S. dollars), with 12 million U.S. dollars coming from the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Polluted Province Strengthens Anti-Pollution Drive
</P>
<P>
Henan Province in Central China plans to build 18 sewage
treatment plants in some major cities in the province.
</P>
<P>
With a total investment of 3.53 billion yuan (425.66 million U.
S. dollars), these plants are capable of treating 1.99 million
tons of waste water every day, a senior official from Henan
Provincial Planning Committee said today.
</P>
<P>
Today construction of 14 of the 18 plants is underway, while
that of the remaining four is expected to begin later this year.
</P>
<P>
"Pine Cancer" Threatening to Forest Reserve in China's World-
Heritage Site
</P>
<P>
"Pine cancer," a dangerous pine disease caused by eelworms, is
now posing a threat to trees in the well-known tourist attraction
of Zhangjiajie State Forest Park in central China.
</P>
<P>
The devastating forest disease was spotted earlier this year in
Enshi Tujia and Miao Autonomous Prefecture in the western part of
Hubei Province, which is only 108 km away from the Wulingyuan
Mountains, which was incorporated into the UNESCO's world heritage
list in 1992 for its abundant virgin forest reserve.
</P>
<P>
Zhangjiajie is situated in the center of the Wulingyuan
Mountains. Pine growing on top of stone cliffs has been regarded
as one of the most famous scenery there.
</P>
<P>
Locust-Stricken Province Wages Anti-Locust Campaign
</P>
<P>
The provincial government of Shandong in east China today
dispatched three planes to spray insecticide to fight locusts in
the Yellow River Delta and surrounding areas.
</P>
<P>
The local government has mobilized more than ten thousand
people to fight the locusts, and so far allocated over nine
million yuan (about 1.023 million U.S. dollars) in funds to
finance the campaign.
</P>
<P>
Garbage Disposal Plant In Hainan To Turn Waste Into Fertilizer
</P>
<P>
China's southernmost province of Hainan has approved the
construction of a garbage disposal plant in the capital city of
Haikou, which will turn 2.8 million tons of domestic garbage
dumped into organic fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
The plant will cost 198 million yuan (23.8 million U.S. dollars)
and have a disposal capacity of 570 tons of garbage a day at the
first phase of construction. It will take a decade to dispose of
the 2.8 million tons of garbage accumulated in the past decade.
</P>
</TEXT>
