<HEADLINE> Iranian President Starts Cabinet Reshuffle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Kicking off his scheduled cabinet
reshuffle, Iranian President Mohammad Khatami on Saturday appointed
Minister of Post, Telephone and Telegraph (PTT) Mohammad Reza Aref
as vice president and chairman of the newly-formed State Management
and Planning Organization (SMPO).
</P>
<P>
The SMPO is a merger of the Planning and Budget Organization
(PBO) and the Civil Administration and Recruitment Organization
(CARO), the official Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The SMPO will be responsible for drafting policies on national
economic and employment affairs, major issues facing Khatami's
government and the new parliament dominated by his reformist
allies.
</P>
<P>
Khatami also appointed PTT deputy minister Nasrollah Jahangard
as the caretaker, former PBO Chairman Mohammad Ali Najafi and
former CARO Secretary-General Mohammad Baqerian as presidential
advisors.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the reformists won a landslide victory over the
conservatives in the February parliamentary election, President
Khatami was urged to make a big change to his cabinet by removing
those who are not fully coordinated with the reformists.
</P>
<P>
The reformist Iran Daily newspaper said on Tuesday that Khatami
will change at least eight ministers and several vice presidents
following the formation of the reformist parliament on May 27.
</P>
<P>
The daily said the reshuffle will touch first vice president,
vice president for executive affairs, minister of PTT, defense,
culture and Islamic guidance, interior, education as well as
economic and financial affairs.
</P>
<P>
Khatami's current cabinet, formed in August 1997, is a coalition
of the reformist party of Islamic Iran Participation Front (IIPF),
the centralist Party of Constructive Executives of Iran (PCEI) and
the leftist Assembly of Combatant Clergy (ACC) headed by the new
Majlis Speaker Mehdi Karrubi.
</P>
<P>
However, relations between the IIPF and the PCEI soured before
the February parliamentary elections as the IIPF strongly opposed
the participation of former President Hashemi Rafsanjani in the
polling while the PCEI supported Rafsanjani to run for a seat.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani, current chairman of the powerful advisory State
Expediency Council, quitted his seat in the Majlis (Parliament)
though the Guardians Council, the top election watchdog, promoted
his position to 20th from 30th at the list of 30 winners in Tehran
constituency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
