<HEADLINE> Saudi-Yemeni Border Treaty to Forge Closer Ties: Saudi Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIYADH, June 17 (Xinhua) -- A recently-signed border treaty
between Saudi Arabia and Yemen will contribute to closer ties
between the two neighbors on the Arabian Peninsula, said Saudi
Interior Minister Nayef Bin Abdul-Aziz Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The treaty for land and sea borders between Saudi Arabia and
Yemen has been signed thanks to the resolve and strong will of the
leaderships of the two countries, Aziz said at a press conference
held in the Red Sea port city of Jeddah.
</P>
<P>
He expressed belief that the two countries from now on will be
linked by stronger ties other than borders or pieces of land here
and there, the Saudi news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia and Yemen Monday signed a final land and sea
border agreement, following persistent bilateral efforts aimed to
solve their long-running border dispute.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that resolving standing issues with a view to
maintaining stability will serve the interests of the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The treaty will in no doubt promote security coordination
between the two countries, especially on border areas, said the
minister, adding security is one of the issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the signing of the treaty will open different
areas for bilateral cooperation and Saudi investors will hopefully
be allured to explore Yemeni markets. And there will also be Saudi-
Yemeni joint ventures in Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
He affirmed that bilateral cooperation was in place even before
the signing of the treaty, and the border disputes have in no way
affected amity, understanding and cooperation between the two
brotherly countries.
</P>
<P>
He also denied allegations that his country solved its border
problems with neighboring countries without fairness, saying that "
We did not take one single meter out of any country." 
</P>
