<HEADLINE> Guatemala Not to Boost Border Surveillance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to reports reaching here from Guatemala City,
Belizean Prime Minister Said Musa asked British military,
political, financial, and technological support until the
territorial conflict with Guatemala is settled.
</P>
<P>
Britain guaranteed Musa the presence in Belize of a defense
unit known as "Batsub," said the Belizean Government press office.
</P>
<P>
Guatemalan Vice President Francisco Reyes commented in answer
to this report that his country is not aggressive and considers
unnecessary the British support to its former colony.
</P>
<P>
Reyes said that his country will continue seeking a solution to
the controversy the peaceful way, at a national as well as at an
international level.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Juan de Dios Estrada also said that no additional
troops will be deployed to guarantee the security in the border
with Belize, because "it is unnecessary."
</P>
<P>
Guatemalan Foreign Vice Minister Ramiro Ordonez said that the
announcement of military support to Belize is "a pretext" to avoid
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Guatemalan diplomacy considers the Belize request to Britain as
a tactical maneuver to continue propagating internationally the
image of Guatemala as a warring country that will attack Belize at
some moment.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, a member of the so-called Belize Council,
Alberto Herrarte, said that the presence of British ships and
troops in the country could be considered in the country as "an
act of intimidation" that must not cause concern to Guatemalans.
</P>
<P>
Belize obtained unilaterally its independence from Britain on
September 21, 1981, and Guatemala acknowledged the fact 10 years
later by establishing diplomatic relations, but without renouncing
to its claim of the 12,000 square kilometers it has in that
territory.
</P>
<P>
A meeting of the Guatemalan and Belizean foreign ministers is
scheduled for July at the Organization of American States (OAS),
which acts as a mediator in the controversy.
</P>
<P>
The meeting's goal is to agree on a summit of the chiefs of
state of the two countries to look for a solution to the conflict.
</P>
