<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "La Nina" Weather Phenomenon to Last Until End of the Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Peruvian scientist, national coordinator for the "El Nino"
phenomenon Biological Impact Monitoring Network, made up of
Ecuador, Colombia, Chile, Peru, and Panama, alerted about the
sequels of this phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
Tarazona explained that "La Nina" will cool the sea temperature
below normal limits and will cause serious climate disturbances in
Peruvian soil.
</P>
<P>
Another of the effects will be the apparition of opaline waters
in the Pacific Ocean, defective in oxygen, that will diminish the
presence of schools of fish and will reduce the productivity of
fishing activities, said Tarazona.
</P>
<P>
Peruvian authorities have also warned that this meteorological
phenomenon has produced high tides along the Peruvian coast with
floods and paralyzed fishing with traditional means.
</P>
<P>
Some experts disagree about the duration of the phenomenon.
Some said that it is in a waning cycle, but others warned that it
will last until the first months of next year.
</P>
<P>
The biological indexes show that La Nina will intensify with
the arrival of winter and will continue until the last days of the
year, said Tarazona.
</P>
<P>
The phenomenon has also caused natural disasters in Chile,
where there have been recently torrential rains with floods and
material damages.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000617.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Neurologist on Impact of Genetic Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Advances in genetic research,
such as the sequencing of the human genome, open the door for new
approaches to the discovery and development of drugs and the
practice of medicine, said a renowned American neurologist.
</P>
<P>
In a review supplement published in the latest issue of Nature
magazine, Allen Roses, a member of the prestigious (U.S.)
Institute of Medicine, put into context what the information
yielded from the human genome means for identifying drug targets
and using those targets to discover new medicines.
</P>
<P>
Roses predicted that pharmacogenetics, the study of how
individual genetic differences influence the variability in
patients' responses to drugs, will improve the prescribing process
by enabling physicians to select, at the time of diagnosis, the
medicine most likely to be safe and effective for the individual
patient.
</P>
<P>
"There is still much work to be done to convert information
from the human genome into better medicine," Roses said in the
review. "Once we have found a gene which predisposes individuals
to a certain disease, it could take 10-15 years before a medicine
results."
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the ability to use information from patients'
DNA to more accurately prescribe medicines that are more likely to
be beneficial and less likely to cause serious side effects, will
occur sooner than many think.
</P>
<P>
In three to five years, he said, new techniques in
pharmacogenetics will enable a physician to compare a small part
of an individual's genetic profile to a "medicine response profile
" to predict whether the patient is likely to benefit from a given
medicine or is likely to experience side effects.
</P>
<P>
Roses also explained a concept of how it may be possible to use
DNA technology to establish an enhanced drug surveillance system.
The current system documents adverse events reported during the
use of a medicine in clinical practice but often there is little
no predictive information to help patients who are subsequently
prescribed the medicine.
</P>
<P>
He said that blood samples for DNA analysis could be taken from
patients who receive a new medicine. In the event of a rare but
serious side effect, the DNA samples of those who experience the
side effect can be compared with samples of those who did not.
This will enable differences in DNA that are associated with the
side effect to be identified and incorporated into a medicine
response profile. DNA from subsequent patients can then be used to
identify those who are susceptible to the side effect before the
medicine is prescribed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000617.0176 </DOCNO>
