<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia's ELN Invites FARC to National Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Antonio Garcia, ELN second commander said Saturday that he has
no idea of the way this meeting will be held, but that he expects
the FARC to present its political plans.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman of the ELN, the second in importance guerrilla
force in the country after the FARC, said that the convention will
be held in the encounter zone, that includes the municipalities of
Cantagallo and San Pablo, in the northern department of Bolivar,
and El Yondo, in the neighboring department of Antioquia, an area
of 4,800 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the problems between the ELN and the FARC, Garcia
said that "it is like a family with brothers and sisters who
despite having the same parents and the same background, have
problems and difficulties."
</P>
<P>
The El Espectador daily commented that the ELN is acknowledging
with its invitation to the FARC a real fact, which is the
historical permanence of the FARC in the El Yondo zone, which
would result in a linking of the two processes of peace
negotiations with the government.
</P>
<P>
"The most important part of all this is that the participation
of the FARC could generate a coordination of the positions of the
different guerrillas in the peace process, which would be ideal
for a constituting process, to which the negotiations are
pretended to be directed," commented the El Espectador newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The Andres Pastrana government started peace talks in January
of 1999 with the FARC, and also started some weeks ago direct
talks with the ELN.
</P>
<P>
 The FARC, which controls about 40 percent of Colombia and is
Latin America's largest and oldest surviving leftist rebel force,
is engaged in a slow-moving peace talks with the government. But
no cease-fire deal has been agreed on as part of the peace process,
which is aimed at ending a conflict that has taken 35,000 lives
over the last decade.
</P>
<P>
 The FARC has some 1,5000 members, while the ELN has 5,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
