<HEADLINE> Computer Failure Causes Flight Chaos in Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 17 (Xinhua) - Air passengers across Britain still
face long delays late Saturday after a problem with a National Air
Traffic Services (NATS)computer.
</P>
<P>
British Airways has canceled several flights to Europe, and the
British Airports Authority (BAA) has advised all passengers to
check with their airlines before leaving home.
</P>
<P>
BBA's Ann Brophy said: "There are going to be delays. What we
don't want is lots of people coming to the airport only to be told
to come back tomorrow."
</P>
<P>
It was announced that Gatwick and Heathrow have been worst hit
but Mancheste, Belfast and Glasgow have also been affected.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for NATS said the computer problem had caused a "
nightmare" for holidaymakers. He advised tourists to keep in touch
with their tour operator or airline to find out what delays they
faced.
</P>
<P>
Observers said many of the hundreds of people delayed at the UK
's busiest airport, Heathrow, were incredulous that a single
technical failure could cause problems on such a scale.
</P>
<P>
NATS has promised a "thorough investigation" into the computer
breakdown, the second time the system has failed in a week.
</P>
</TEXT>
