<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuelan President Hails Rio Group Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez
said Saturday that "a Bolivian and revolutionary current" pervaded
Rio Group's 14th Summit held in Cartagena, Colombia from June 15
to 16.
</P>
<P>
Chavez said in statements made at his arrival in Caracas back
from the Colombian port in the Caribbean resort city that this
current arrived to the Rio Group and the ideology of liberator
Simon Bolivar floated in all the region.
</P>
<P>
The Venezuelan president said that the outstanding topics
during the Latin American chiefs of state summit were the defense
of sovereignty and the need of regional integration.
</P>
<P>
He said that if the development of the Cartagena summit and its
results are compared to those of other previous meetings, great
differences can be seen about the goal of integration
</P>
<P>
Chavez, who was one of the presidents most chased by the press
in Cartagena because of his irreverent and frank speech on
international issues , said he was satisfied with the results of
the meeting of the 19 countries.
</P>
<P>
The Venezuelan president proposed during the Latin American
conclave, in which for the first time participated as full
members the Central American countries, the creation of a Latin
American Monetary Fund (LAMF) as an instrument against the
assailing of the international financial conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
The Declaration of Cartagena signed by 15 heads of state and
four presidential delegates proposed the creation of a new
international financial architecture and defined the area's
position toward the Summit of the Millennium convoked by the
United Nations for September.  
</P>
</TEXT>
